comments.body:
Looked at this issue with [~spark]. AWS does not present any limit for this field in their documentation. We currently should be limiting the DNS name (readable part) to 253 characters per specification but we don't seem to limit each label to the maximum 63 characters required per spec. 

from RFC-1034:
{quote}Each node has a label, which is zero to 63 octets in length.  Brother
nodes may not have the same label, although the same label can be used
for nodes which are not brothers.  One label is reserved, and that is
the null (i.e., zero length) label used for the root.{quote}

{quote}To simplify implementations, the total number of octets that represent a
domain name (i.e., the sum of all label octets and label lengths) is
limited to 255.{quote}

[~chuck], the label length check is in LoadBalancingService.createLoadBalancer, around line 368:

{code}
			if(!HostSpecifier.isValid(String.format("%s.com", arg0)))
{code}

see the bug description for how this should be changed.

In LoadBalancerDnsRecord, we are testing the DNS name against the maximum name length (253) but not against the max label length (63).
{code}
        final int maxPrefixLength = 253 -
                String.format(".%s.%s", LOADBALANCER_DNS_SUBDOMAIN,
                        SystemConfiguration.getSystemConfiguration().getDnsDomain()).length();
{code}

The solution is to add a check that ensures the dnsPrefix variable does not exceed the remainder of 263 or 63.
{code}
        final int maxPrefixLength = java.lang.Math.min(63, 253 -
                String.format(".%s.%s", LOADBALANCER_DNS_SUBDOMAIN,
                        SystemConfiguration.getSystemConfiguration().getDnsDomain()).length());
{code}

AWS rejects creation of a load balancer if the name exceeds 32 characters in length: 

{code}
        $ aws elb create-load-balancer --load-balancer-name
         abcdefghijabcdefghijabcdefghijabcdefghijabcdefghijabcdefghijabcdefghij
         --scheme HTTP --availability-zones us-west-1a --listeners
         '{"instance_port": 80, "load_balancer_port": 80, "protocol": "HTTP"}'
         {
            "ErrorResponse": {
                "RequestId": "6597d9b7-f94b-11e2-871b-6b24fccecfc3",
                "Error": {
                    "Message": "LoadBalancer name cannot be longer than 32
         characters",
                    "Code": "ValidationError",
                    "Type": "Sender"
                }
            }
         }
{code}

Applied and tested the following fix successfully:

{code}
nanuk:loadbalancing chuck$ git diff --color fd984997cf2ff14e60f73e5a08df022d5f5d8ac4 LoadBalancingService.java 
diff --git a/clc/modules/loadbalancing/src/main/java/com/eucalyptus/loadbalancing/LoadBalancingService.java b/clc/modules/loadbalancing/src/main/java/com/eucalyptus/loadbalancing/LoadBalancingService.java
index c361164..80cf732 100644
--- a/clc/modules/loadbalancing/src/main/java/com/eucalyptus/loadbalancing/LoadBalancingService.java
+++ b/clc/modules/loadbalancing/src/main/java/com/eucalyptus/loadbalancing/LoadBalancingService.java
@@ -374,6 +374,13 @@ public class LoadBalancingService {
     if(!nameChecker.apply(lbName)){
        throw new InvalidConfigurationRequestException("Invalid character found in the loadbalancer name");
     }
+
+    // To be AWS compatible, the ELB name must not exceed 32 characters. To remain DNS compliant, in case
+    // AWS increase this number in the future, the ELB name must never exceed 63 characters.
+    if(lbName.length() > 32){
+       throw new InvalidConfigurationRequestException("Loadbalancer name must not exceed 32 characters");
+    }
+
     if(request.getListeners()!=null && request.getListeners().getMember()!=null)
        LoadBalancers.validateListener(request.getListeners().getMember());
     
nanuk:loadbalancing chuck$ 
{code}
